54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>This is the Vertical In=
tegrator mantra: </span><strong>better, faster, cheaper, at higher margins<=
/strong><span>. Primer is applying it to a $1.5 trillion US education marke=
t ($870 billion of which is </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect=
/b627788b-6542-46ea-85df-a3201ca5faec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);text-=
decoration: underline;">spent on public elementary and secondary schools</a=
><span>) &#8211; a gargantuan market whose impact as a multiplier on all ot=
her markets is even larger.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color:=
 rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">In its first deck, Andur=
il wrote &#8220;Anduril is a company that will save Western civilization by=
 saving taxpayers hundreds of billions of dollars a year as we make tens of=
 billions of dollars a year.&#8221;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color=
: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Primer is pursuing that=
 same promise in education &#8211; if it can provide kids with a better edu=
cation at scale for a third or less of the cost of the traditional public s=
chool system, it will save our youth by saving taxpayers hundreds of billio=
ns of dollars a year as they make tens of billions of dollars a year.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-si=
ze: 16px;">That seems overly optimistic if you view Primer in the context o=
f traditional EdTech companies, which despite their lofty missions have gen=
erally failed to produce generational companies. But if you think about Pri=
mer as a company whose top line approaches the budgets of US public school =
systems at high and growing margins, it tracks.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 =
20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>Today=
, Primer owns a </span><em>minuscule</em><span> percentage of the overall m=
arket. There is much work to be done &#8211; technological, operational, an=
d pedagogical &#8211; to even scratch that opportunity. And given the turni=
ng tides for school choice in America, there will be plenty of legitimate c=
ompetition (not to mention a flood of &#8220;competition&#8221; from standa=
lone AI tutors, a seeming threat we discuss in the conversation). Education=
 will not be a winner-take-all market, and it shouldn&#8217;t. But there wi=
ll be a </span><em>biggest </em><span>winner, and my bet is that Primer wil=
l be it.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line=
-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Ryan told me that Primer is making three be=
ts:</p><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0;padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0=
 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0=
;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;"><stro=
ng>That there will be a Moore&#8217;s Law for Education</strong><span>: tha=
t software will help deliver a better and better education for a lower and =
lower cost.</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-=
box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;"><strong>That teachers can=
 be excellent entrepreneurs:</strong><span> Primer is relying on teachers i=
n local communities to attract students and provide them with a great educa=
tion.</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;pa=
dding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;"><strong>That it&#8217;s possibl=
e to scale physical schools quickly with asset-light real estate:</strong><=
span> that by skipping the high CapEx and long timeline buildouts both publ=
ic and private schools undertake, Primer can move faster and cheaper and fo=
cus on the thing parents actually care about: teaching their kids.</span></=
p></li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height=
: 26px;font-size: 16px;">To me, this is one bet, and it&#8217;s the thesis =
against which I&#8217;ve invested in Primer two more times since that initi=
al 2021 investment:</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);=
line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>It is possible to build a bette=
r school system, one that gets better and costs less over time. To do that,=
 you need to build something that </strong><em><strong>looks </strong></em>=
<strong>like the existing school system, but that has some of the scale and=
 financial characteristics of a technology business.</strong></p><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16=
px;">That&#8217;s what Primer is building. It offers physical schools. Its =
teachers teach a core curriculum in the morning, and then give kids the fre=
edom to pursue their curiosity in the afternoon. As states pay more in scho=
larships and Primer lowers costs, it can offer a product that is free to cu=
stomers at growing margins. Using technology but not defined by it, Primer =
can offer students an education that gets better as Primer grows, until it =
can provide a better education for any family that wants one.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16=
px;">Which sounds great on paper, but which is really, really hard in pract=
ice. Ryan and I discuss those challenges and the tremendous opportunity in =
our Follow-Up Conversation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54=
